@NODE "Display" "Display"
@TOC "MAIN"

                   Chris Lansdowne - Graphic Artist

       People will unfortunately compare the display quality of
    Windows running on an SVGA monitor against Workbench running on
    an A1200 plugged into, say, a Philips CM8833.  Or worse still a
    portable TV.

       Treat your Amiga to a VGA or MultiSync and it will wipe the
    floor with the PC every time.  If you've never seen it don't
    prejudge.  Bear in mind that The CM8833 et al. are basically
    low resolution CGA monitors.

       Only the Amiga could display that many colours and look that
    good on a CGA monitor or TV!  If you want to output from a PC
    to a TV remember a half-decent VGA-TV adaptor costs a couple of
    hundred quid and still wouldn't look as good as Commodore's TV
    modulator.

       Amiga 1200 and 4000 owners should, at the least, purchase a
    cheap VGA colour monitor.  It will plug straight into their RGB
    port using the supplied adaptor and will make Workbench and
    programs such as word processors that run on standard screens
    look a lot better than the PC equivalents.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Pricing" "Comparing prices..."
@TOC "MAIN"

         Harry Ord - Market Analyst Specialising in Computers

       There is a common error that people make when comparing
    prices between different platforms, especially when they look
    at adverts for PCs.

       They think 260mb hard disk, what a bargain!  They forget
    that on a PC this doesn't go as far as on an Amiga.

       I've seen the Amiga version of a program come on two 880k
    floppies, whilst the PC version is on 8 high density disks.

       The Amiga has custom chips to perform such tasks as hardware
    scrolling and to provide hardware sprites etc.

       On the PC such routines have to be performed by the code
    itself, that's why there's so much of it.

      As well as custom chips, the Amiga has libraries for common
    operations.  This cuts down on the length of programs
    considerably.

       My son's Amiga has a tiny (20mb) hard disk drive, containing
    Workbench, Protext, Dpaint and other applications software.  He
    still has plenty of room for data.  On a PC you would lucky to
    fit DOS, Windows and just ONE word processor in 20 megs!

       When you consider the extra code and all of the separate
    video and sound drivers that have to be installed on a PC for
    each program you will arrive at a hard disk comparison ratio of
    above 5 to 1.  That's to say that a 250mb hard disk fitted to a
    PC is only equal in real terms to a 50mb hard disk fitted to an
    Amiga.

       The price of an entry level PC is too high for the average
    consumer.  The PC could really take off as a home computer if
    they could make one that cost less than Ł400.  They could try
    to get it down to this price by putting it in a low-cost casing
    like the Amiga 1200.  [How would you add a sound card? - Ed].

       Selling PCs without monitors would also help reduce the
    starting price.  Most people have a TV and are happy to use
    that for their display, buying a monitor later when funds
    allow.

       The trouble is that getting a PC to talk to a domestic TV is
    complex and expensive.  The designers of the Amiga knew what
    they were doing when they devised the display chips.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Architecture" "Architecture"
@TOC "MAIN"

                       Rob Needham - Programmer

       I don't like the PC architecture.  It was designed in the
    late seventies.  Modern innovations have to be "bolted" on.  In
    order for programs to use any memory above 640k you have to
    also run patch programs, extended memory managers and the like.
    As things need more resources you just add more and more
    patches.  The biggest patch of all has to be Windows.

       Eventually, a time comes when you have to stop papering over
    the cracks and build a new wall.

       The next version of "Windoze" (code-name Chicago) is
    reckoned to need 12mb of RAM, JUST for the operating system!
    PC owners who can't afford to buy the extra RAM will simply
    stick with Windows 3.1.  Trouble is a lot of software will be
    released that won't run under 3.1 and they will get left
    behind.

       The Amiga was designed to run a graphical user interface
    from the very beginning - with the guts of it built into ROM.
    (Kickstart).  Windoze has to load into RAM, swallowing precious
    memory and slowing the machine down.  Instead of re-designing
    the basic hardware and getting rid of these flaws, PC
    manufacturers just increase the speed of the CPU.  Other
    bottlenecks then appear, the RAM chips and videocard can't keep
    up with the CPU, so they apply more patches, extra caches and
    so-called "Windows Accelerators".  The system then becomes very
    top heavy.  It's like refusing to buy a new car, instead,
    getting other cars to push from behind.  Motorola-based
    machines like the Mac and Amiga don't suffer from such
    tribulations and software will run at a decent speed even if
    the processor is only doing 14mhz.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Redundancy" "Redundancy"
@TOC "MAIN"

                   Ian Goudie - Computer Consultant

       My job involves specifying systems to do particular jobs for
    particular firms.  I need to be fully conversant with all of
    the latest software.

       I started with a 8088 XT.  It cost me 1,200 pounds.  I
    resisted upgrading to a 286 which was needed to run the early
    version of Windows.  Then along came Windows 3.0  and with it
    some new software that would only run under Windows 3.0.

       I splashed out a small fortune on a shiny new 286.  Within 8
    months software was regularly appearing which specified a 386
    ast the minimum configuration.  I was forced to spend again.

       Today I have a 486 SX and already I'm finding that too slow
    to run the latest versions of many applications that I need to
    use.

      I hear that the ensuing versions of all the big titles,
    (Lotus, Word etc.) will require even more processing power and
    more memory in order to run at a decent speed.  More processing
    power than the average 486 can provide.

       The next generation of top PC software is only going to run
    properly on a Pentium, or if RISC versions are written, on the
    Power PC.  As soon as the big corporations (who buy 95% of all
    PCs made) upgrade their machines, the software support for the
    older 486s will dry up.  Just like it has for the XTs, 286 and
    386s.  Already the classifieds are full of cheap 286 and 386
    machines that nobody wants.

       The PC market is corporate led, and it's always the
    individual users who get left behind when the market moves on.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Doom" "Doom and all that..."
@TOC "MAIN"

             Stuart Legge - Independent Computer Retailer

       The kind of people that we used to get in were owners of
    Atari STs and Amiga 500s.  They'd seen 486 PCs playing Doom and
    wanted in.  One guy had had an Amiga 500 since 1988 and
    complained that software support for his 1.3 A500 was becoming
    thin on the ground.  Bless him.  If he'd bought a PC in 1988
    he'd have been back for a new machine @{"long ago" LINK "Redundancy"}.

       The guy felt let down by Commodore, and wasn't going to buy
    an AGA machine, oh no, he'd seen Doom and he thought it was the
    start of the next games revolution!

       Of course what he witnessed in Doom is the end of the PC
    games revolution.  PC games just won't get much better.  Doom
    is it.  It's a fluke, a by-product of the inefficient old
    fashioned way the PC handles graphics.

       We still sold him a PC, a thousand pounds is a lot of money
    for a game of Doom.

       When people come to us for games consoles we used to sell
    them Megadrives and Nintendos, now we sell them CD-32s.
    Nothing can touch the CD-32 for the price.  Computer Trade
    Weekly reports that the CD-32 format accounts for more than 50%
    of all games sold on @{"CD-ROM." LINK "CD-ROM"}  That's more than Sega MegaCD, PC-
    CD and CDi put together!

       Sure, in time, the next generation of consoles will probably
    eat CD-32 alive.  But at least if you have an ageing CD-32 you
    can add a keyboard and disk drive and use it as a 32 bit home
    computer, something you won't be able to do with your Sega or
    Nintendo.  Roll on the CD-64!


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Standards" "Standards"
@TOC "MAIN"

                          Eddie - Amiga User

       People tell me to buy a PC because it's the "standard"
    machine.  This is the biggest misconception about PCs ever.  If
    you grabbed every PC in a ten mile radius you would have a room
    full of several different makes of machines, with 4 different
    floppy disk standards, numerous graphics standards, mouse
    standards, joystick standards, soundcard standards and even bus
    standards.

       They say that if you buy a PC it's like buying a VHS video
    and you needn't worry about it becoming @{"obsolete." LINK "Redundancy"}  My ageing
    Amiga 500+ runs a much larger percentage of today's new
    software than any of the PCs that were around at the time that
    I bought it.

       I think that the Amiga on a card for PC is a good idea.  It
    would serve to introduce more people to the delights of the
    Amiga.  Sell more Amiga magazines.  Sell more Amiga software.
    Ultimately, folks using one at work, for @{"multimedia" LINK "MultiMedia"} say, when
    looking for a machine to use at home would ignore the PC part
    and just buy the Amiga!

       The Intel chips are a joke.  The software companies were
    producing more and more sophisticated software that needed
    better and better processing power.  Intel now clocks the chips
    at ridiculous speeds, bolting fans on to them to stop them
    melting.  IBM and others are saying enough is enough.  It's
    time for a new architecture.  The PC as you know it is a dying
    dinosaur.  Bring on the RISC machines, the Power Mac, Power PC
    and Power Amiga!


@ENDNODE

@NODE "MultiTasking" "MultiTasking"
@TOC "MAIN"

             "Yabbadabbadoo" - Comms phreak and PC-Owner.

       Everyone goes on about how the Amiga can multi-task.  When I
    had my Amiga I never thought that I used that function.  I was
    downloading from A BBS the other day to my PC.  Unfortunately I
    didn't have enough hard disk space left for the files coming
    in, and no way of making space while I was on-line.

       On the Amiga, while my comms package would be running in the
    background downloading a load of stuff, Opus would be
    formatting a blank in one drive, un-DMSing to a disk in the
    other drive AND extracting some other files from an lha
    archive!

       Sometimes I'd even be listening to a tracker mod that I'd
    just downloaded, all at the same time.  The thing about real
    multitasking, is that you don't miss it until you get a PC.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "WordProcessing" "Word Processing"
@TOC "MAIN"

                     Nancy Trenholme - Journalist

       The PC has more word processing packages available for it
    than the Amiga.  In real life though people tend to only use
    one favourite package.  Friends tell me how great Microsoft
    Word is, and I've tried it.  Yet I can't see anything that you
    can *actually* do in Word that you can't do with Final Writer
    or Wordworth, neither can they!


@ENDNODE

@NODE "High Street" "High Street"
@TOC "MAIN"

            Nigel French - High Street Chain Shop Manager.

       We've always sold Amigas and now also sell 486 PCs.  There
    are a lot of people who come into our shops who want to buy a
    computer for their kids.  They only ever want to spend a few
    hundred pounds at the most.  No way can we persuade these
    people to buy an expensive high-end PC.

       Since the demise of the Atari ST the only choice in this
    important price bracket is the Amiga.  The Amiga 1200 is
    fantastic value and now has the sub-Ł500 market to itself.

       There always has and always will be plenty of software
    support for a good low-cost machine, so owners of high-end
    Amigas benefit from the sales of the low-cost 1200s.  There are
    no low-cost PCs, unless you count the 286s which no-one
    supports now anyway.

       The PC is too complicated for the average person who doesn't
    know enough about computers generally.  If they buy the kids an
    Amiga for Christmas and granny buys them a few games, come
    Christmas morning all they have to do is shove a disk in the
    drive.

       With PCs, it's different.  "What soundcard?  Joystick?
    Graphics card?"  And that's the easy bit!  When it comes to
    allocating DMA channels, setting interrupts and editing
    config.sys files  they are totally flummoxed.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Brands" "Cheap Brands"
@TOC "MAIN"

                        Anothy Norak - PC Owner
       I like the PC and have owned a 486 machine for over a year.
    One thing that I would urge potential PC purchasers to think
    about is the brand that they buy.

       It's odd how the people who wouldn't dream of buying a cheap
    brand VCR or hi-fi, Matsui, Alba, Amstrad etc. don't apply the
    same principle to buying a computer.  I spent extra to buy a
    good brand PC .  Friends of mine have bought "no-name" cheap
    clones to save money.

       This is a false economy.  Cheap brand PCs are banged
    together as fast and as inexpensively as possible.  The  build
    quality is hardly inspiring.  The calibre and life-expectancy
    of the bundled keyboard and monitor is often meagre.  Getting
    repairs can be tricky too, most companies will carry out
    repairs to  your "El Cheapo" clone, but a lot refuse to
    guarantee the work.

       You ask me about Amigas, I've never used one, but have heard
    that they are only good for playing games.  I don't think that
    you can @{"word process" LINK "WordProcessing"} or do DTP on them.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Sony" "Sony"
@TOC "MAIN"

                     The Microsoft Intel Monopoly
       When Commodore put itself up for sale, rumoured to be among
    the potential bidders was the Japanese electronics giant Sony.
    What is interesting about Sony is that they have never really
    had a crack at the personal computer market.  Apparently it
    wouldn't suit them to market a PC clone, tying themselves to
    American giants like Intel and Microsoft.

       Sony are planning to break into the games market with their
    forthcoming PlayStation console, and at the moment, computer-
    wise,  that is what they are concentrating on.

       No doubt though, one day, Sony will launch a full-blown
    computer that will compete with the IBM PC and its compatibles.
    They could start from scratch, or what is more likely, buy up
    and develop a tried and tested technology.

       As any industry pundit can tell you, the Amiga has the best
    @{"operating system" LINK "MultiTasking"} of ANY desktop computer, the name and design
    are well established.  Combine this with Sony's flair for
    marketing, and their ability to back this up with the necessary
    cash and you can see the attraction.

       What would also attract someone like Sony to the Amiga is
    that it and its software is thee industry standard for video
    and TV work.  This would fit in nicely with Sony's domestic and
    broadcast video products.

       If the Amiga technology comes up for sale again in the
    future don't be surprised to see some interest from one or more
    Japanese giants determined to break the Microsoft-Intel
    monopoly.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Piracy" "Piracy"
@TOC "MAIN"

                                Piracy
       Piracy is a problem, the computers that suffer the greatest
    piracy start to receive the least software support.

       I appeal to the hardened pirates reading this.  Even if you
    just occasionally, once in a blue moon, bought something
    legitimately, or sent off a few pounds to a shareware author,
    you'd then be helping to guarantee future software support for
    your machine.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "MultiMedia" "MultiMedia"
@TOC "MAIN"

                              MultiMedia
       I have an Amiga 4000.  I use it for DTP, raytracing and
    video presentation work.  Thanks to the custom chips and its
    close compatibility to video standards it excels at multimedia.

       Once you've created your pictures, sounds and animations the
    best program for linking them all together is Scala.  It is the
    best multimedia authoring system on ANY computer.

       When IBM introduced "OS2 for Windows with MultiMedia
    Extensions" in the US earlier this year, there was a big press
    launch.  At this event was a huge videowall promoting the new
    system.  As many magazines reported at the time, the wall was
    driven by an Amiga 2000 running ScalaMM200!  Ironic, or what.

       I've seen desktop video systems for the PC and they just
    aren't in the same league as their Amiga counterparts.  I've
    now started using Lightwave for my 3D work and it is brilliant,
    totally beating the pants off Autodesk's 3D Studio and costing
    a couple of thousand less!

       Lightwave is the same software that they use in Hollywood
    with the Video Toaster for producing special effects for
    feature films and TV series.  The PC has got better
    spreadsheets than the Amiga, but at the end of the day the
    score is:- Babylon 5 - Lotus 123.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Data Interchange" "Data Interchange"
@TOC "MAIN"

                  Compatibility and Data Interchange
       Just for fun, imagine that God put the secrets of the
    Universe and the entire meaning of life onto computer disks
    split into three parts.  Not likely I know, but I did say just
    for fun.

       Part One was on an MS-Dos formatted disk.  Part Two on a
    Macintosh formatted disk.  Part Three on an AmigaDOS disk.

       Only the owners of one of those computers would be able to
    read all three parts!

       As well as reading disks from the other two, the Amiga can
    write to and format Mac and MS-Dos disks with ease.  It is also
    more efficient at using floppy disks, a 3.5" DSDD disk can hold
    880k of data, a HD disk 1760k.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "DOS" "Disk Operating Systems"
@TOC "MAIN"

                        Disk Operating Systems
       We run a model agency. We provide models for photographic
    and general promotions work.  All of the portfolios are stored
    on computer with digitised pictures of the models.

       We used to have an Olivetti PC for doing this, but now use
    an Amiga.  We chose the Amiga for a reason that wouldn't be
    obvious to most people.

       On the Amiga, filenames can be as long as 31 characters, be
    in mixed-case and include spaces.  This allows us to give
    expressive names to the pictures we have stored on disk.

       The PC only allowed us an 8 letter name and a 3 letter
    extension.  "Jayne Smith Blonde 5ft 8in" would be called
    JSMITHBL.GIF.  You can imagine the confusion and mix-ups that
    this caused.

       We still use the PC - for accounts, but if someone wrote a
    decent high-end accounts package for the Amiga we would use
    that instead.  We much prefer the way the Amiga works.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "CD-ROM" "CD-ROM"
@TOC "MAIN"

                                CD-ROM
       Recently I fitted a CD-ROM drive to my machine, an
    Amiga1200.  Initially this was just so that I could run CD-32
    games software. The great thing about the CD standard is that
    the format of PC and Amiga disks are the same.
    Apple Mac disks tend to use their own structure, but the Amiga
    can even read them too thanks to CrossMAC.

       All this means that I can view all of the pictures on any
    Amiga, Mac, CD-32, PC or Photo CD, load PostScript fonts, read
    text files and listen to sounds.  It can be a very cheap way of
    getting large amounts of data.  A coverdisk from a recent issue
    of PC Format magazine had hundreds of tracker modules on it,
    all of which play on the Amiga.  (The .mod standard originated
    on the Amiga anyway.)

       Though your Amiga can access the data on PC CD-Roms, you
    can't run the programs; well that's not totally true, you can
    if you use an emulator such as PC Task, but this is slow.

       So, the solution would be to put an Amiga version of the
    program on the CD as well.

       If you look at the basic constitution of a CD-Rom, such as
    those that contain encyclopedias, you would see that 80 - 90%
    of what's contained is data and not programs.  Therefore it
    would be very feasible to release CDs that would work on both
    machines.

        On such a dual format CD there would be one version of the
     main exe program for the Amiga and one for the PC.  Both
     programs using the same picture and sound data.
@ENDNODE

